#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:376
msgid "Object Ownership"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:378
msgid ""
"JavaScript and C++ have very different memory models which can lead to it "
"being unclear which language owns and is responsible for deleting an object "
"when it moves between languages. To make object ownership more explicit, "
"*embind* supports smart pointers and return value policies. Return value "
"policies dictate what happens to a C++ object when it is returned to "
"JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:384
msgid ""
"To use a return value policy, pass the desired policy into function, method, "
"or property bindings. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:393
msgid ""
"Embind supports three return value policies that behave differently "
"depending on the return type of the function. The policies work as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:396
msgid ""
"*default (no argument)* - For return by value and reference a new object "
"will be allocated using the object's copy constructor. JS then owns the "
"object and is responsible for deleting it. Returning a pointer is not "
"allowed by default (use an explicit policy below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:399
msgid ""
":cpp:type:`return_value_policy::take_ownership` - Ownership is transferred "
"to JS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:400
msgid ""
":cpp:type:`return_value_policy::reference` - Reference an existing object "
"but do not take ownership. Care must be taken to not delete the object while "
"it is still in use in JS."
msgstr ""

