#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:726
msgid "Base classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:728
msgid "Base class bindings are defined as shown:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:737
msgid ""
"Any member functions defined on ``BaseClass`` are then accessible to "
"instances of ``DerivedClass``. In addition, any function that accepts an "
"instance of ``BaseClass`` can be given an instance of ``DerivedClass``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:742
msgid "Automatic downcasting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:744
msgid ""
"If a C++ class is polymorphic (that is, it has a virtual method), then "
"*embind* supports automatic downcasting of function return values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:760
msgid ""
"Calling ``Module.getDerivedInstance`` from JavaScript will return a "
"``Derived`` instance handle from which all of ``Derived``'s methods are "
"available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:764
msgid ""
"*Embind* must understand the fully-derived type for automatic downcasting to "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:767
msgid "*Embind* does not support this unless RTTI is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:771
msgid "Overloaded functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:773
msgid ""
"Constructors and functions can be overloaded on the number of arguments, but "
"*embind* does not support overloading based on type. When specifying an "
"overload, use the :cpp:func:`select_overload` helper function to select the "
"appropriate signature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:797
msgid "Enums"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:799
msgid ""
"*Embind*'s :cpp:class:`enumeration support <enum_>` works with both C++98 "
"enums and C++11 \"enum classes\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:825
msgid ""
"In both cases, JavaScript accesses enumeration values as properties of the "
"type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:834
msgid ""
"You can control how C++ enums are exposed to JavaScript by specifying "
"``enum_value_type`` when registering the enum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:837
msgid ""
"By default, enums use ``enum_value_type::object``. Enum values are bound as "
"JavaScript objects with a ``value`` property containing the underlying C++ "
"integer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:856
msgid "Alternatively, you can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:858
msgid ""
"``enum_value_type::number``: Enum values are bound directly as JavaScript "
"numbers matching their C++ integer values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:874
msgid ""
"``enum_value_type::string``: Enum values are bound as JavaScript strings "
"containing their name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:889
msgid ""
"Regardless of the ``enum_value_type`` used, enum values can always be used "
"as arguments to functions expecting the enum type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:918
msgid "Constants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:920
msgid "To expose a C++ :cpp:func:`constant` to JavaScript, simply write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:928
msgid "``SOME_CONSTANT`` can have any type known to *embind*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:934
msgid "Class Properties"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:936
msgid ""
"By default ``property()`` bindings to objects use ``return_value_policy::"
"copy`` which can very easily lead to memory leaks since each access to the "
"property will create a new object that must be deleted. Alternatively, use "
"``return_value_policy::reference``, so a new object is not allocated and "
"changes to the object will be reflected in the original object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:943
msgid "Class properties can be defined several ways as seen below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:999
msgid "Memory views"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:1001
msgid ""
"In some cases it is valuable to expose raw binary data directly to "
"JavaScript code as a typed array, allowing it to be used without copying. "
"This is useful for instance for uploading large WebGL textures directly from "
"the heap."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:1006
msgid ""
"Memory views should be treated like raw pointers; lifetime and validity are "
"not managed by the runtime and it's easy to corrupt data if the underlying "
"object is modified or deallocated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:1028
msgid ""
"The calling JavaScript code will receive a typed array view into the "
"emscripten heap:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:1037
msgid ""
"The typed array view will be of the appropriate matching type, such as "
"Uint8Array for an ``unsigned char`` array or pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:1044
msgid "Using ``val`` to transliterate JavaScript to C++"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/embind.rst:1046
msgid ""
"*Embind* provides a C++ class, :cpp:class:`emscripten::val`, which you can "
"use to transliterate JavaScript code to C++. Using ``val`` you can call "
"JavaScript objects from your C++, read and write their properties, or coerce "
"them to C++ values like a ``bool``, ``int``, or ``std::string``."
msgstr ""

